7:18:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=68.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> More on The Overthere Kiting</span><hr size=1> Thanks for the encouraging words guys.  I'm almost level 37 now (less than a bubble away).  <br>
<br>
I'm able to dual-kite almost every time.  A couple of strategies have come developed for this level range. <br>
<br>
1.  Get three and round them up.  Snare.  Those that resist, run off and root.  Go back and get the two you snared and kill them.<br>
<br>
2.  Often, I end up having to finish the mobs one at a time.  With variable resist rates, I may end up with one snared mob almost-dead and stationary and another still chasing me.  They're now separated.  I must finish them off separately.<br>
<br>
3.  While re-rounding and re-snaring is good experience for me (not XP wise but learning), it wastes so much mana I can almost never finish off even one mob.  I did succeed in a tri-kite early yesterday but the last Sarnak Knight was wandering slowly away, unsnared, and I was totally OOM.  I asked an SK to help but the guards got him.  Ugh.<br>
<br>
4.  MoB speed is key.  I will never attempt Rhinos and Tigers.  I can barely stay ahead of the Tigers and the Rhinos will run me down with TBoots.<br>
<br>
5.  It's gotten easier to snare as I've gained XP.  <br>
<br>
6.  I've begun solo-kiting Sarnaks, Cocks, and Succulents without snaring them first.  Using my TBoots, I just run ahead until my Staff of Temp Flux says I'm out of range, stop, do not turn, cast nuke, run.<br>
<br>
7.  You don't need to turn and face the snared MoBs to nuke them.  Just get out of range, stop, nuke, keep running.  <br>
<br>
8.  The biggest single reason to stay at The Overthere is I'm Amiable with VS now.  Hence, I can sit in the tunnel-entrance way to the Outpost with two nasty guards on either side of me, go AFK for 10 min whilst I meditate, come back, dual-kite, go sit in total safety again.  <br>
<br>
Plus, when things really do go bad (like I had a Tiger agro on me and I had one bub of health left) I can run to mommy and daddy guards for salvation.  <br>
<br>
